It's not a commander I particularly enjoy playing against, having to set aside time at the end of each turn so the Feather player can cast that uncommon from Stronghold to draw 2. But there's plenty of commanders way more guilty  of that kind of thing.

I don't think I have much opinion on Teshar. I think every color should be allowed to have combo decks, if that's the underlying question. I think they're a bad look for a precon commander, though.
And to be clear, I actually like the design of things like K'rrik. He's busted but he's at least fascinating. Feather's gameplay might be repetitive but she's a joy of new design space.
Stuff like Gerrard seems like the worst of both worlds to me. He's not opening a new door. The Adarkar Valkyrie trick is interesting but you could also just play Avacyn. Teshar at least opens a new door. It's not one I'll enjoy, but it at least opens something. One of the questions they asked in the GDS3 was what the main goal of a commander from a precon should be. The answer was that it should make people want to build something new and original and make them consider interactions they'd never considered before. That's a high bar, but it's the goal they set for themselves and when it isn't reached, I don't have any qualms about saying so.

While I appreciate and enjoyed your answer, my question was much simpler in intent :sweat_smile:  You said you like Feather and I feel like Teshar is similar in the looping interactions, which is why I enjoy both.
The moral of the story is that no matter what you think about boros, you're still wrong for not playing Selesnya

Usually most popular ends up being the most recognizable, which is the only reason I suggest it. On top of that, the 3 color combinations were the first ones supported by Commander products, which is what my reasoning was there as well. 

Most popular always doesn’t mean most recognizable, but it’s something we can decide on a case-by-case basis, IF that was the idea we wanted to go with.

Regardless of whatever idea we choose, we need to make sure that the commanders we use are recognizable and iconic. Having a thematic through-line will also help with allowing characters to be recognized. It’s why cycles are popular in the first place.
